04135nam a22006615i 9780814768259DE-B159720200608045044.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200608t20122012nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2011033400  a97808147682597 a10.18574/97808147682592doi  a(DE-B1597)548587  a(OCoLC)775441366  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aBX7056.Z5bP58 2016 7aREL0790002bisacsh04a262.149732231 aPitt, Richard N., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDivine Callings :bUnderstanding the Call to Ministry in Black Pentecostalism /cRichard N. Pitt. 1aNew York, NY : bNew York University Press, c[2012] 4c©2012  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1 The Church of God in Christ -- t2 "Heard a Voice from Heaven Say" -- t3 "All the World's a Stage" -- t4 "A Stutter And A Stick" -- t5 "Don't Quit Your Day Job" -- t6 "Chew the Meat and Spit Out the Bones" -- t7 Legitimating New Understandings of Ministry and the Clergy -- tAppendix -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex -- tAbout the Author 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOne of the unique aspects of the religious profession is the high percentage of those who claim to be "called by God" to do their work. This call is particularly important within African American Christian traditions. Divine Callings offers a rare sociological examination of this markedly understudied phenomenon within black ministry. Richard N. Pitt draws on over 100 in-depth interviews with Black Pentecostal ministers in the Church of God in Christ-both those ordained and licensed and those aspiring-to examine how these men and women experience and pursue "the call." Viewing divine calling as much as a social process as it is a spiritual one, Pitt delves into the personal stories of these individuals to explore their work as active agents in the process of fulfilling their calling. In some cases, those called cannot find pastoral work due to gender discrimination, lack of clergy positions, and educational deficiencies. Pitt looks specifically at how those who have not obtained clergy positions understand their call, exploring the influences of psychological experience, the congregational acceptance of their call, and their response to the training process. He emphasizes how those called reconceptualize clericalism in terms of who can be called, how that call has to be certified, and what those called are meant to do, offering insight into how social actors adjust to structural constraints.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 08. Jun 2020) 0aAfrican American clergy. 0aVocation, Ecclesiastical. 7aRELIGION / Christianity / Pentecostal & Charismatic.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNYUP Backlist 2000-2013z978311070644440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814768259423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780814768259.jpg  a978-3-11-070644-4  NYUP Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK